<vulnerability_guide>
  <title>WEBRTC VULNERABILITIES</title>

  <critical>WebRTC enables peer-to-peer communication directly in browsers, but it can leak private IP addresses through STUN/TURN, expose SRTP keys, enable SRTP injection attacks, and provide vectors for cross-protocol attacks. Many privacy extensions and VPNs are bypassed by WebRTC.</critical>

  <scope>
    - IP address leakage (VPN bypass)
    - STUN/TURN server exploitation
    - SRTP encryption weaknesses
    - Peer-to-peer data channel attacks
    - Media manipulation
    - Consent and privacy attacks
  </scope>

  <methodology>
    1. IP ADDRESS LEAKAGE
       {% raw %}
       # WebRTC leaks local and public IPs through STUN
       # Works even through VPNs and proxies

       # JavaScript to enumerate IPs
       <script>
       const pc = new RTCPeerConnection({
         iceServers: [{urls: "stun:stun.l.google.com:19302"}]
       });
       pc.createDataChannel("");
       pc.createOffer().then(offer => pc.setLocalDescription(offer));
       pc.onicecandidate = ice => {
         if (ice.candidate) {
           console.log(ice.candidate.candidate);
           // Extract IP from candidate string
         }
       };
       </script>

       # Leaked information:
       # - Local network IP (192.168.x.x, 10.x.x.x)
       # - Public IP (bypasses VPN)
       # - Interface enumeration
       # - Network topology hints
       {% endraw %}

    2. STUN/TURN SERVER ATTACKS
       {% raw %}
       # Test for open STUN servers
       stunclient stun.target.com 3478

       # STUN request types to test
       # Binding Request - basic IP reflection
       # Allocate Request - TURN relay allocation

       # TURN credential brute forcing
       # TURN requires authentication
       # Test common credentials:
       # - guest:guest
       # - turn:turn
       # - webrtc:webrtc

       # TURN server abuse
       # Can be used to relay arbitrary traffic
       # TCP tunneling through TURN
       # UDP amplification vectors
       {% endraw %}

    3. SRTP ATTACKS
       {% raw %}
       # WebRTC uses SRTP for media encryption
       # DTLS-SRTP key exchange

       # Key exchange weaknesses:
       # - DTLS downgrade attacks
       # - Certificate validation bypass
       # - Weak cipher suites

       # SRTP replay attacks
       # If replay protection is weak:
       # - Replay encrypted packets
       # - Cause audio/video glitches
       # - Potential for DoS

       # Master key extraction
       # If you can access browser memory:
       # - Extract SRTP master keys
       # - Decrypt all media traffic
       {% endraw %}

    4. DATA CHANNEL EXPLOITATION
       {% raw %}
       # WebRTC DataChannel uses SCTP over DTLS
       # Allows arbitrary data exchange

       # Test for:
       # - Input validation on received data
       # - Message size limits
       # - Binary data handling

       # Injection through DataChannel
       # If app trusts peer data:
       # - XSS through data channel messages
       # - Command injection
       # - Deserialization attacks

       # SCTP vulnerabilities
       # Chunk fragmentation attacks
       # Association hijacking
       {% endraw %}

    5. CONSENT AND PERMISSION ATTACKS
       {% raw %}
       # WebRTC requires user consent for media
       # But consent mechanisms can be bypassed

       # Permission prompt attacks:
       # - Clickjacking on permission dialog
       # - Timing attacks on permission state
       # - Persistent permission abuse

       # Screen sharing exploitation:
       # - Trick user into sharing sensitive window
       # - Capture credentials, 2FA codes
       # - Record screen without obvious indicators
       {% endraw %}
  </methodology>

  <advanced_techniques>
    <srtp_injection>
      {% raw %}
      # If on network path, can inject SRTP packets
      # Requirements:
      # - Knowledge of SSRC (can be sniffed)
      # - Guess or know sequence numbers
      # - Be in network position

      # Impact:
      # - Inject audio into call
      # - Replace video frames
      # - Disrupt communication

      # SRTP-SRTCP injection differs
      # SRTCP index is separate from RTP sequence
      {% endraw %}
    </srtp_injection>

    <fingerprinting>
      {% raw %}
      # WebRTC reveals significant fingerprinting data

      # Extractable information:
      # - Supported codecs (audio/video)
      # - Media device enumeration
      # - Network interface characteristics
      # - ICE candidate types

      # Device fingerprinting
      navigator.mediaDevices.enumerateDevices()
        .then(devices => {
          devices.forEach(d => console.log(d.deviceId, d.label));
        });

      # Codec fingerprinting
      RTCRtpSender.getCapabilities('video').codecs
      RTCRtpSender.getCapabilities('audio').codecs
      {% endraw %}
    </fingerprinting>

    <mitm_attacks>
      {% raw %}
      # DTLS-SRTP relies on certificate fingerprints
      # Exchanged via signaling (usually SDP)

      # If signaling is compromised:
      # - Replace certificate fingerprints
      # - Perform MITM on media stream
      # - Decrypt, inspect, re-encrypt

      # SDP manipulation
      # Modify a=fingerprint: lines
      # Insert attacker's certificate

      # Protection: Certificate transparency for WebRTC
      # But rarely implemented
      {% endraw %}
    </mitm_attacks>

    <cross_protocol_attacks>
      {% raw %}
      # WebRTC speaks multiple protocols
      # STUN, TURN, DTLS, SRTP, SCTP

      # Protocol confusion attacks:
      # - Send HTTP to STUN port
      # - Send STUN to web server
      # - Exploit protocol parser differences

      # Rebinding through WebRTC
      # Use ICE to establish connection to internal host
      # Bypass same-origin policy
      {% endraw %}
    </cross_protocol_attacks>

    <dos_attacks>
      {% raw %}
      # WebRTC DoS vectors

      # ICE flooding
      # Send many ICE candidates
      # Exhaust connection attempts

      # DTLS handshake flooding
      # Initiate many incomplete handshakes
      # Resource exhaustion on peer

      # Media flooding
      # Send high bitrate media streams
      # Bandwidth exhaustion
      {% endraw %}
    </dos_attacks>
  </advanced_techniques>

  <detection>
    - Monitor for unexpected WebRTC connections
    - Check for IP leakage in browser tests
    - Audit STUN/TURN server configurations
    - Review DataChannel message validation
    - Track media permission grants
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Successfully extract real IP through VPN
    - Enumerate internal network addresses
    - Demonstrate STUN/TURN server abuse
    - Fingerprint user through WebRTC APIs
    - Identify data channel input validation issues
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - WebRTC IP leak works in iframes - great for tracking
    - mDNS candidates were added to mitigate IP leak but don't fully work
    - TURN servers can tunnel TCP traffic for proxy bypass
    - getUserMedia can be used to activate cameras without visual indicator in some browsers
    - Chrome://webrtc-internals shows detailed WebRTC stats
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>WebRTC was designed for peer-to-peer communication which inherently requires IP address exchange. This fundamental design means IP leakage is a feature, not a bug. VPN users are particularly vulnerable. Always test WebRTC endpoints for both security vulnerabilities and privacy implications.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
